    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-11-05T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-11-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="420"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d420">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.94/2406</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Adviser on Political Relations</hi> (<hi
                        rend="italic">Hornbeck</hi>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-11-05">November 5,
                            1941</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The reasoning in this telegram,<note n="81" xml:id="d420fn81">No. 1736, November
                        3, 1941, 3 p.m., from the Ambassador in Japan, <ref
                            target="frus1931-41v02#pg_701">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, Japan, 1931–1941, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>, p. 701</ref>.</note> as in many which have
                    preceded it, runs to the general effect that, although Japan misbehaves, we must
                        <pb facs="0577" n="569" xml:id="pg_569"/> not apply strong pressures to
                    Japan—because that would probably cause Japan to do things which would bring on
                    war, in which case the fault would be ours; rather, we must conciliate Japan, by
                    making concessions; but, in doing this, we must not recede one inch from our
                    fundamental principles. Mr. Grew says: “It is equally far from my intention for
                    a single moment to advocate so-called ‘appeasement’ on the part of the United
                    States or that our Government should in the slightest degree recede from the
                    fundamental principles which it has laid down as a basis for the adjustment and
                    conduct of international relations including our relations with Japan. Methods
                    may be flexible but with principles there should be no compliance [<hi
                        rend="italic">compromise</hi>].”</p>
                <p>Query (again): Might it not be appropriate for us to ask the Tokyo Embassy to
                    give us <hi rend="italic">its</hi> concept of what might be the provisions of a
                    “settlement” between the United States and Japan—in harmony with and applying
                    the above.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>S[<hi rend="smallcaps">tanley</hi>] K. H[<hi rend="smallcaps"
                            >ornbeck</hi>]</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
